To solve the cycle detection problem for an undirected graph using Disjoint Set Union (DSU),
also known as the Union-Find algorithm,
we process each edge and check if the two endpoints already belong to the same set.

Initialize: Each node is its own representative (0, 1, 2, 3, 4).
Edge (1, 3): Union(1, 3). Sets share a root.
Edge (3, 0): Union(3, 0). Now {1, 3, 0} are in one set.
Edge (0, 2): Union(0, 2). Now {1, 3, 0, 2} are in one set.
Edge (2, 4): Union(2, 4). All nodes {1, 3, 0, 2, 4} are in one set.
Edge (0, 4): We call find(0) and find(4). Both return the same root representative.

Conclusion: Since they share a root, adding the edge (0, 4) creates a cycle. 


class Solution {
    static class DSU{
        int[] parent;

        
        DSU(int n){
            parent = new int[n];
            for(int i=0; i<n ;i++){
                parent[i]=i;
            }
        }
        
        int find(int x){
            
            if(parent[x]==x) return x;
               
            
          
          return parent[x] = find(parent[x]);  
        }
        
        boolean union (int i, int j){
            
            int pi=find(i);
            int pj=find(j);
            
            if(pi==pj){
                return false;
            }
            
            parent[pi]=pj;
           return true; 
        }
        
    }
    public boolean detectCycle(int V, ArrayList<ArrayList<Integer>> adj) {
        // code here
        DSU dsu= new DSU(V);
        Set<String> processed= new HashSet<>();
        for (int u=0; u<V; u++){
            
            
        for(int v: adj.get(u)){
            int first = Math.min(u,v);
            int second = Math.max(u,v);
            
            String key= first+"-"+second;
            if(!processed.contains(key)){
                processed.add(key);
            if(!dsu.union(u,v)){
                return true;
            }
            }
        }
        }
        return false;
    }
}
